05867nam a22007455i 9780271094670DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710946707 a10.1515/97802710946702doi  a(DE-B1597)651520  a(OCoLC)1380732036  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aFOR0110002bisacsh04a892.4/09qOCoLC223/eng/202206021 aMintz, Alan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Hebraist :bEssays on Agnon and Modern Jewish Literature /cAlan Mintz; ed. by David Stern, Beverly Bailis. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (284 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDimyonot: Jews and the Cultural Imagination00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAmerican Hebraist: An Introduction -- t1 Agnon’s Childhood -- t2 Agnon in Jaffa: The Myth of the Artist as a Young Man -- t3 Agnon Without End -- t4 In the Seas of Youth -- t5 On “The Sense of Smell” by S. Y. Agnon -- t6 Reading Hahazanim -- t7 Writing About Ourselves: Jewish Autobiography, Modern and Premodern -- t8 Ahad Ha-Am and the Essay: The Vicissitudes of Reason -- t9 Sefer Ha’aggadah: Triumph or Tragedy? -- t10 Israeli Literature in the Minds of American Readers -- t11 Haim Gouri at 90 -- t12 Viva Voce: Vicissitudes of the Spoken Word in Hebrew Literature -- t13 Knocking on Heaven’s Gate: Hebrew Literature and Wisse’s Canon -- t14 Modern Hebrew Literature and Jewish Theology: Repositioning the Question -- t15 Hebrew in America: A Memoir -- tEpilogue: Packing Up an Office; The Work of Mourning and the Creation of an Archive0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlan Mintz (1947–2017) was a singular figure in the American Jewish literary landscape. In addition to publishing six authoritative books and numerous journal articles on modern and contemporary Jewish culture, Mintz contributed countless reviews and essays to literary journals, including the New Republic, the New York Times Book Review, and the Jewish Review of Books. Scattered in miscellaneous volumes and publications, these writings reveal aspects of Mintz’s scholarly personality that are not evident in his monographs.American Hebraist collects fifteen of Mintz’s most insightful articles and essays. The topics range from the life and work of Nobel Prize winner S. Y. Agnon—including a chapter from Mintz’s unfinished literary biography of that author—to Jewish and Israeli literature, the Holocaust, and a rare autobiographical essay. The chapters are introduced and contextualized by Mintz’s longtime colleague and friend David Stern, who opens the book by tracing the arc of Mintz’s intellectual career; the volume concludes with a personal essay and remembrance written by Beverly Bailis, the last student to complete a doctorate under Mintz’s direction.Brimming with erudition and intriguing biographical notes, American Hebraist provides new insights into the life and work of one of the twentieth century’s most important scholars of modern Hebrew literature. Students and scholars alike will benefit from this essential companion to Mintz’s scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Hebrew.2bisacsh  aAlan Mintz.  aAmerican Jewish history.  aHebrew Literature.  aHolocaust.  aJewish Literature.  aJewish Theology.  aS. Y. Agnon.  aidentity.  amodern era.1 aBailis, Beverly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailis, Beverly, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStern, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStern, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/voc